You can do it like this.  But why use a Long[] instead of a primitive array of long[]?  Object wrappers of primitive types have more overhead.  And if you assign them to a primitive type, unboxing is required for conversion.
```java
      Long[] array1 = new Long[ARRAY_SIZE];

	  Random random = new Random();
	  array1 = random.longs(ARRAY_SIZE, 0, 100000).boxed().toArray(Long[]::new);

```

`Random::longs` returns a `LongStream`. So assuming you want to collect it into array `Long[]`, then this should help:

    Long[] array = random.longs(ARRAY_SIZE, 0, 100000)
                         .boxed()
                         .toArray(Long[]::new);

----------

You can check the approach on a shorter stream:

    Long[] array = LongStream.range(0, 10)
                             .boxed()
                             .toArray(Long[]::new);

    for (Long l : array){
        System.out.println(l);
    }

